 Installing and Configuring Apache on Fedora
This section covers installing Apache (`httpd`) on Fedora Server, configuring it, creating a basic website, and ensuring it works in VMware.
 1. Update Fedora
 .................
sudo dnf update -y

2. Install Apache
..................
sudo dnf install httpd -y

3. Start and Enable Apache
...........................
sudo systemctl enable --now httpd
sudo systemctl status httpd

4. Open Firewall for HTTP
...........................
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

5. Create Website Directory
............................
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/mywebsite
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /var/www/html/mywebsite
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/html

6. Add a Basic Homepage
........................
create index.html:
nano /var/www/html/mywebsite/index.html
Replace 'welcome to Imani's website' with whatever you want to appear on the homepage:
<h1>Welcome to Imani's Website</h1>

Save and exit.(ctrl+o,enter,ctrl+x)

7. Test Apache
...............
Open your web browser and visit:
http://<your-server-ip>

You should see either the default Apache page or your homepage.
If you're not sure about your ip you can check it using:
ip a
8. SELinux (If Enabled)
sudo chcon -R -t httpd_sys_content_t /var/www/html/mywebsite

 Note About .gitignore
 ......................
When working with configuration files on Linux, especially for Apache:
- DO NOT upload private keys such as:  
  - `mywebsite.key`  
  - SSL certificates  
  - Password files  
  - Backups  
To prevent uploading sensitive files to GitHub,I created a `.gitignore` file in my repository:
This ensures private server files never get pushed accidentally.


